default2.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe release of Public Sector Information, which is not restricted on grounds of privacy or security, as Open Data, is the most effective way 
defaultof maximising its utility and allowing the nation to 
defaultachieve
default 
defaultmaximum
default benefit from
default the 
defaulttaxpayer 
defaultfunds used to collect the data originally
default.
default&#xa0;
default2.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn addition to re-use, which may generate additional economic activity, Open Data contributes to transparency enabling the public to hold the public sector to account
default for the effective delivery of public services. W
defaulthere 
defaultsuch data
default relates to the quality of public services 
defaultit 
defaultcan often allow the public to exercise informed choice.
default&#xa0;
default2.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMaking information available as Open Data often leads to improvements in quality as errors 
defaultwill
default 
defaultbe noticed and reported by more individuals and organisations
default.
default&#xa0;
default2.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGovernment policy relating to which data should be open, which should be closed
default,
default which should be traded 
defaultand at what prices 
defaulthas been incoherent and has often appeared to be arbitrary
default and lacking in detailed accountability
default.
default&#xa0;
default2.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDespite the agreed policy of a ‘presumption to publish’ t
defaulthe release of public sector 
defaultinformation as Open D
defaultata has often been in
defaultconsistently
default planned 
