defaultPASC’s questionsdefault&#xa0;
default1. Why is open data important?default&#xa0;
default1.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultInformation has become the key economic resource of the 21
defaultst
default century. The economic 
defaultefficiency and the 
defaultcompetitiveness of nations will depend on the choices that are made over how data is collected and shared to maximise the opportunities of deriving information from it.
default&#xa0;
default1.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPrivate companies have a clear obligation to use data, in the same way as any other resource, to maximise the return to shareholders.
default&#xa0;
default1.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSome private companies achieve this by 
defaultapparently 
defaultmaking the data they collect, create or collate openly available. This is usually not the case as
default, often, users are only permitted
default to view the data,
default not to capture and reuse it. 
defaultMaking the data ‘open’ to view only is a mechanism 
defaultto attract users to view advertising material that is placed
default alongside it, and data reuse is limited
default to prevent the collation of information
default by others.
default&#xa0;
default1.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultG
defaultenuinely Open Data from the private and 
defaultvoluntary 
defaultsectors is rare. Wikipedia and OpenstreetMap.org are notable exceptions
default; 
defaultboth 
defaultare 
defaultnot-for-profit organisations that allow the relatively free re-use of their data.
default&#xa0;
default1.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn the age of broadband and superfast broadband the internet has become a ubiquitous 
defaultchannel of communication
default. 
defaultOnce initial data hosting costs are covered 
defaultthe marginal cost of sharing data 
defaultis 
defaultclose to zero
default and
default allows the release of Open Data as a public good at a substantially lower cost than previous mechanisms for disseminating data which carried significant costs. It is this technological change that has created the Open Data opportunity.
default&#xa0;
default1.6
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAround the world many governments are coming to the conclusion that maximising the amount of Open Data available to citizens and businesses is the way to maximise the economic benefit that countries as a whole can derive from that data. This is particularly the case for Public Sector Information (PSI) which has already had to be collected in order to allow government departments or agencies to fulfil their Public Task
defaults
default. European regulations on the re-use of PSI strongly encourage the release of as much of it as possible as Open Data (subject to privacy or security constraints) in order to maximise its re-use and the economic activity related to its re-use.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default2.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultGovernment has had 
defaultperiodic 
defaultmajor strategic reviews of the release and charging mechanisms for 
defaultpublic sector information, in particular 
defaultstatistical information
default and core reference data
default.
default Perhaps the most significant ones have been
default:
default&#xa0;default2.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultT
defaulthe 
defaultRayner Review of 1979default, which led indirectly to a Tradable Information policy being introduced by the Treasury which lives on in guidelines for charging for government information.
default&#xa0;
default2.3.
default&#xa0; 
defaultTh
defaulte
default 
defaultRayner R
defaulteview created a situation where vital statistical information, and in particular Census Information was no longer freely available even to Government Departments, but had to be purchased through “Census Agencies”, private sector brokers who paid a licence 
defaultfee for the exclusive right to re-sell government statistical information.
default 
defaultThis led to some government departments claiming that they were no longer able to afford to pay for the information necessary to carry out aspects of their Public Tasks
default.
default&#xa0;
default2.4.
default&#xa0; 
default“Crown Copyright in the Information Agedefault”default publisheddefault in 1998default.default Rather than taking a strateg
defaultic view of what data should be o
defaultpen and how it should be funded, this review divided agencies into those that were successfully recovering a significant proportion of their costs by trading in information, such as Ordnance Survey
default (OS)
default, and should continue to do so, and those not recovering significant costs which were liberated to release their data without charge, such as 
defaultthe Office for National Statistics
default (ONS)
default.
default 
defaultThe impact of this 
defaultseemingly 
defaultpragmatic decision was to create a difficult divide between the trading agencies and the Open Data agencies.
default&#xa0;
default2.5.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAddressing and geospatial data is of particular value 
defaultto 
defaultall aspects of our 
defaultsociety
default. Its pseudo-c
defaultommercialisation as tradable data underpins much of the complexity found in the public sector information landscape where many publ
defaultic sector bodies re-purchase 
defaultdata 
defaultfrom one-another in
default 
defaultan overly complex, inefficient system which re-cycles
default public money 
defaultbetween publicly owned entities.
default&#xa0;
default2.6.
default&#xa0; 
defaultFurther complexities in licensing and re-use of public sector information arise from this system particularly where so-called ‘derived-data’ restrictions are put in place by the data holders. For example Ordnance Survey place restrictions on both public sector and private sector organisations re-using 
defaulttheir own data,
default once it has been combined in some way with OS data.
default 
default&#xa0;
default2.7.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAs an
default example,
default in
default 
defaultpreparing for the 2001 Census
default the ONS found itself unable to afford all the geographical data from the OS which would have been helpful in conducting the Census.
default  
defaultFollowing the publication of 2001 census results in 2003,
default 
defaultONS found that it was unable to release 
defaultthe census 
defaultoutput area boundaries
default (OAs)
default as 
defaultunrestricted 
defaultOpen Data, because of Ordnance Survey’s com
defaultmercial interests in that data.
default&#xa0;
default2.8.
default&#xa0; 
defaultA consultation on default‘defaultPolicy options for geographic information from Ordnance Surveydefault’default in 2009default led to the 
defaultdecision 
defaultto 
defaultrelease some 
defaultOrdnance Survey (OS) 
defaultdata as 
defaultOpen Data
default, and the Public Sector Mapping Agreement (PSMA) which makes OS data available for free to the public sector
default. This
default was a significant change of policy, though it did not appear to be part of an overall strategy
default and excluded the Royal Mail Postcode Address File (PAF)
default. OS negotiated with a nominated “intelligent customer” as to which products should be released as Open Data. These included administrative and statistical boundaries in BoundaryLine and Postcode locations (though not the locations, or the text, of individual addresses). 
defaultThis was a significant step forward
default for the Open Data agenda
default, but 
defaultdid not deliver a
default coherent Open Data strategy.
default&#xa0;
default2.9.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe 
defaultCabinet Office Open Datadefault White paper and the subsequent defaultShakespeare Reviewdefault both make cogent and compelling cases for Open Data. However neither can be regarded as a strategy and, while they have led to the release of over 10,000 government data sets, these have not been released or prioritised according to any discernible strategic framework. Nor is there any regulatory mechanism to ensure 
defaultongoing 
defaultpublication, release or change update strategies for 
defaultthe 
defaultdata sets that have been released.
default&#xa0;
default2.10.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn order for the country to gain the maximum utility and economic advantage from Open Data a more strategic response is needed. There needs to be a single, permanent, locus in government for the regulation of Open Data release and for the dissemination of a coherent strategy which will outline: 
default(i) 
defaultwhat should be released; 
default(ii) 
defaulthow it should be released; 
default(iii) 
defaulthow frequently dynamic data sets 
defaultshould 
defaultbe updated or whether, by simply exposing dynamic data sets, users 
defaultshould
default 
defaulttrack change
defaults
default themselves; 
default(iv) 
defaultwhat metadata standards should be used 
default(data.gov.uk delivers a quasi standard and the recent National Information Infrastructure guidelines for departments are an additional step) 
defaultand
default; (v) 
default what skills and funding are required to ensure that the Open Data strategy is sustainable.
default 
default&#xa0;
default2.11.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn the short term the Cabinet Office has taken on this role enthusiastically
default and is achieving some good results
default. 
defaultHowever the 
defaultoverall 
defaultremit is spread across many public sector bodies including the
default Office for Public Sector Information
default, the 
defaultInformation Commissioner’s Office
default,
default The Department for Business 
defaultInnovation
default and Skills (BIS)
default, 
defaultd
defaultata holders within individual departments
default and their agencies
default, Local 
defaultAuthorities
default and other public 
defaults
defaultector 
defaultd
defaultata holder
defaults
default. These bodies do not work effectively together which we suggest is as a result of 
default(a) the historic complexity of the legislative and executive landscape; and (b) 
defaulta lack of overall strategy
default and priorities for Open Data
default and 
defaultO
defaultpen 
defaultD
defaultata standards
default.
default&#xa0;defaultright onesdefault?default&#xa0;default3.1
default&#xa0; 
defaultT
defaulthe Government’s stated aims for the release of 
defaultO
defaultpen 
defaultD
defaultata and the stated key outcomes of the 
defaultO
defaultpen Data Strategy are entirely appropriate and laudable. We support them strongly.
default&#xa0;default3.2
default&#xa0; 
defaultHowever we cannot be sure that there is a 
defaultcoherent 
defaultcommitment to the Open Data Strategy from all government departments. 
defaultThe government
default appears to be resolutely focussed on relatively small revenue streams arising from some of the Trading Funds and a short term focus on raising one-off revenues through the privatisation of public assets, which include fundamental datasets. As a result 
defaultboth parts of BIS and the Shareholder Executive 
defaultare pushing forward short-term policy decisions which undermine the fundamentals of the
default Open Data Strategy.
default&#xa0;default3.3
default&#xa0; 
defaultWhile the release of individual data sets is valuable, some data is essential to make other data sets meaningful. This is sometimes referred to as “Core Reference Data”, items of data which will be used across many data sets 
defaultas identifiers to show what a record relates to
default. This data
default need
defaults
default to be 
defaultmaintained and disseminated from a single source. Examples are: addresses with postcodes
default and geo
default-
defaultcoordinates
default; geographical codes for statistical or administrative areas; company registration numbers; VAT numbers; codes or standardised names for health or 
defaulteducational establishments
default; NHS numbers; Social Security numbers
default, classifications for public administrations and their services
default.
default&#xa0;default3.4
default&#xa0; 
defaultSome p
defaultersonal identifiers are contentious and should not be released as Open Data except as part of a system that anonymises records and preserves and protects the privacy of individuals. Others are, or should be, matters of public record, these include Company Registration Numbers, VAT registrations
default.
default&#xa0;default3.5
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe decision by BIS to allow Royal Mail to take the Postcode Address File (PAF) into private ownership as a commercial data set, and for Ordnance Survey to participate in the creation of GeoPlace LLP as a trading Value Added Reseller of PAF which intends to commercially exploit geographically referenced addresses appears to fly in the face of any Government commitment to Open Data.
default&#xa0;default3.6
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Office for National Statistics has consistently explained how essential a single National Address Register is for a wide range of statistical purposes from taking a reliable Census, through Census alternatives to the sampling and geographical aggregation of many other surveys.
default&#xa0;default3.7
default&#xa0; 
defaultFor users of statistics it is very important to know what set of addresses ar
defaulte
default included in each statistical area so that other data can be matched reliably to data from ONS, or data can be submitted to ONS reliably. It is difficult to understand how this can be accomplished effectively if a National Address 
defaultR
defaultegister is not available as Open Data.
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default4.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe availability of government datasets as part of the National Information Infrastructure, including a single underlying platform of Core Reference Data needs to be agreed, delivered and maintained.
default&#xa0;default4.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultGovernment analysts and statisticians should make the widest possible use of this data, to avoid the inefficiency associated with multiple dataset-capture and maintenance of essentially identical sets of public sector information.
default&#xa0;
default4.3.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe use of single data repositories will enable im
defaultproved like-for-like comparison and
default peer review in the generation of management information and statistics. Open 
defaultD
defaultata allows improved levels of analysis and innovation, and will also increase the quality of the underlying data (the more users of a given dataset the higher the number of issues which will be detected and can be rectified).
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default5.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultBy enforcing the current presumption to publish a
defaultnd
default making sure all new data collection and IT contracts: (i) do not duplicate what is already collected by others; (ii) are designed with the release of Open Data as an upfront requirement. This should apply to all public bodies i.e. Central and Local Government.
default&#xa0;default5.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultSustainable funding 
defaultis essential to ensure that public sector information is made available, and continues to be available as Open Data. This can be achieved by ensuring that the cost of exposing data on an open platform is included in the initial cost of any project requiring data (this is generally likely to be a marginal overhead on the basic data collection cost
defaults).
default&#xa0;
default5.3.
default&#xa0; 
defaultWhere data is generated as a result of statutory registration, such as: Land Registration, registering to vote, being registered to pay Council Tax or Business Rates, registering a planning application or building regulations consent etc. the cost of registration should include an element used to make the data collected openly available.
default&#xa0;
default5.4.
default&#xa0; 
defaultA principle of charging those who cause 
defaultO
defaultpen 
defaultD
defaultata to change, rather than those who seek to use it, should be adopted as government policy.
default 
defaultCitizens 
defaultalready pay to register births, deaths, marriages, cars, companies, land, planning applications, building permits and many other transactions. Each of these cause official data to change. A fee charged to a person registering, or causing, a change in an official record, should include an element that pays for that data to b
defaulte included and disseminated as Open D
defaultata. This is a much
default more efficient way of funding Open D
defaultata than closing the data and charging for 
defaultits 
defaultuse
default. It requires fewer tra
defaultnsactions, the sum
defaults
default involved 
defaultare a s
defaultmall percentage of 
defaultthe fees being paid 
defaultand collected
default anyway and the amount
default collected is directly proportional to the update effort so there is no need to speculate how many times data will be used to set a price. This is a fair, efficien
defaultt and effective way of funding Open D
defaultata generated as part of a public task.
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default6.1
default&#xa0; 
default(a) The default requirement for CSV format is adequate in the first instance. Moves to deliver Linked Data formats are welcome, but not essential. The provision of APIs is useful in some use cases, but it does not constitute a proper Open Data solution to deliver a service (ie: pre-analysed or aggregated results) without allowing for the bulk download of the underlying data.
default&#xa0;default6.2
default&#xa0; 
default(a) 
defaultWhile releasing data in a useful format is helpful and desirable, the minimum requirement should be that data is first released in the format used to deliver the public task for which it was collected. This minimises delay and cost in data release and it is likely that the Open Data community, or value adding re-processors will quickly adapt the data into more usable formats
default. This is the “Raw data now!” principle proposed by Sir Tim Berners Lee, which states that the release of data should be the prime requirement, while improving it to make it more usable is secondary.
default&#xa0;default6.3
default&#xa0; 
default(a) Where possible data should make use of existing standards and reference common vocabularies to enable the comparison and combination of data, therefore enhancing its reuse. 
defaultOpen Data should comply with the Open Data Certificate 
defaulthttps://certificates.theodi.org/
default.
default&#xa0;default6.4
default&#xa0; 
default(b) 
defaultAt a minimum m
defaultetadata concerning the available data formats, size of dataset, provenance (data owner),
default 
defaultlatest update (date), frequency of release, data holder (contact details) 
defaultand reference to any common vocabularies 
defaultshould be provided. 
default&#xa0;default6.5
default&#xa0; 
default(b) 
defaultA number of more complete metadata standa
defaultrds such as Dubli
defaultn Core and UK Gemini exist and are useful. However the requirement to provide complete metadata to these standards is often a barrier to Open Data release. It is for this reason that we suggest that a very simple metadata record should be treated as essential, while full standard metadata records are regarded as nice to have and can be added after data release.
default&#xa0;default6.6
default&#xa0; 
default(c) Society
default will use the data. It should be freely 
defaultusable by anyone; public sector
default, 
defaultvoluntary and not-for-profit sectors, 
defaultprivate sector, researchers
default and 
defaultindividual citizens.
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default7.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultdata.gov.uk has been successful in providing a 
defaultfocal point for Open Data and a 
defaultmechanism for the release of datasets which are not currently traded.
default It has been successful in starting to change attitudes and behaviours in the public sector about the rationale for and opportunities to release public sector information as Open Data.
default 
defaultHowever, the main focus is on meeting central government departments’ information publishing needs. data.gov.uk needs to consider the data publishing requirements of the wider public sector, including local government and other public bodies. 
defaultIt is too early to say how widely this data is used, but the provision of a simple mechanism and a single location for data release 
defaultand to locate available datasets is essential.
default 
